ratings.question_text: Your level of engagement with the course was:
What is your overall assessment of this course?
The course was well organized to facilitate student learning.
I received clear feedback that improved my learning.
Relative to other courses you have taken at Yale, the level of intellectual challenge of this course was:
Relative to other courses you have taken at Yale, the workload of this course was:

narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned about prominent philosophies in Chinese historyConfucianism, Moism, Buddhism, Taoism, etc.and how they have influenced one another. I also learned how to critically read and analyze texts from a variety of different sources, interpret the meaning behind their writing style and structure, and discover commonalities/differences among texts from the same or different time periods. I also gained a more comprehensive understanding of the timeline of Chinese dynastic history.

- How to read dense texts
- How to look closely at texts
- Focused discussion of texts
- Close analysis vs general discussion

WR Credit - learned how to write a literature paper, refreshed my close reading skills, insight into the classics of Chinese literature and ancient Chinese philosophy, how to discuss literature in section
Close reading, cross-examining textual influences

This course provides a broad overview of Chinese literature from the beginnings of the Shang and Zhou dynasties to the early 20th century. I learned a bunch about how to analyze primary sources with a focus on exegesis rather than relying on context. This course also taught me to pay attention to the form of a primary source and its relation to the content.
Learned a lot about the Chinese tradition  covering a very long period of time. Good general overview.

Understanding of ancient Chinese history
How tradition evolves, is used over time
Read and understand ancient texts
How to analyze texts critically
I learned about how to analyze texts and write concisely, and also about the Chinese Tradition.

Some skills: Close reading, historical analysis, comparing and contrasting texts, how form influences content. I learned more about the history of the Chinese tradition , how it has changed/not changed over the years.
Reading.
I learned how to closely read a passage and how to explore the Chinese culture without only looking at context.
I learned more about close reading texts and analyzing literary strategies from authors of Chinas past.
Understanding of how to analyze ancient Chinese texts
Chinese history through the perspective of literature, how to evaluate arguments based on the form of authors' works instead of the specific diction
I learned the history of Chinese philosophy.
Analyzing texts based on their medium rather than ideas
Close reading, understanding of the thinkers and works of literature that have defined the Chinese tradition
I learned about Ruism, Chinese philosophers, poems, plays, and the dynasties. Some skills I picked are: close reading, comparing passages, critical thinking.
learned a lot about chinese literature and philosophy, but most importantly, how to write a thoughtful paper based on a text
I improved close reading abilities and learned about form
I learned how to best read, analyze, and compare classic Chinese texts over Chinese history, as well as how to write effectively in order to convey these thoughts.

I gained a broad overview of pre-modern Chinese texts and history, beginning from the Analects and concluding in the early 20th century. I practiced focusing on the relationship between form and function in my essays.

I learned about a broad overview of Chinese history and thinking through various literary texts. I also learned about how to read primary sources closely and how to write long essays on short piece of works, which helps with critical thinking skills.
Learned a lot about Chinese history and literature, but also gained close reading skills and a greater appreciation for the form of the texts that I'm reading.
Close reading skills, and a greater understanding of Chinese history, philosophy, and culture

This course gave me a really good introductory background to the Chinese intellectual tradition from the first dynasty to the 20th century. Sourcing material from a wide variety of authors, genres, ideologies, and narrative forms, this course introduces students to the wide diversity of the Chinese academic canon. I also learned how to actually analyze passages and formulate my own opinions on it in a meaningful way.

I gained a comprehensive overview of Chinese dynastic history. I definitely learned how to read a text closely and think critically about why the author wrote in a particular and selected the words that they did without situating their writing in the historical context in which they were written.
I developed my knowledge of Chinese history, and worked on analyzing/comparing material.
Pretty much what the course says! I learned a lot about Chinese culture through each dynasty's most famous texts.
how to engage with Chinese literature
I learned a lot about premodern Chinese history through lectures regarding historical context and primary source readings.

I learned a lot about Chinese history, philosophy, its evolution over time, and how it has shaped what we consider Chinese tradition and culture. There were a lot of close-readings involved and we really delved in deep to analyze just a sentence or 2, picking out every detail there was. I was in the Chinese section, so it was incredibly fascinating to read the original texts instead of the English translated versions because I often find that the translation does not sufficiently capture the original meaning.
How to write a comparative analysis piece and find new mediums for it.
I learned about Chinese tradition through the earliest texts until near-modern times

I learned a lot about pre-modern Chinese history, philosophy, religion, politics, and culture! I gained insight into a lot of the ancient Chinese texts and philosophies and developed my close reading and textual analysis skills.
I learned more about Chinese history, reading older texts, and about philosophy's impact on Chinese culture.

Learned about the Chinese tradition - basically Chinese intellectual history from antiquity up to about the 20th century. Professor emphasized close reading texts - a lot of the focus was on dissecting shorter passages and focusing on textual evidence, rather than on fitting things into larger contexts

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: Strengths: the professor and TA were engaging. Weaknesses: sometimes unclear what parts of the texts we read we should focus on, or what our learning goals were.

- Not stressful week to week, but very targeted skills it teaches
- Strong involvement of instructor and TA

Too much of a focus on literature/philosophy. I wanted more of a balance between literature and history. Professor also liked to cold call students which most people didn't like. Most of the readings felt too long which dissuaded me from doing them

TAs were great, the material felt beginner-friendly, and the selected readings were genuinely interesting

This course is very much a "you get what you put in" type situation. There were only three projects (5-7 pages essays for WR sections) throughout the semester, 2 15-minute asynchronous lectures per week, and less than 100 pgs of reading per week. In my opinion, this made the class less stressful, but I still felt like I got a lot out of it. Because we got to choose our own passages to analyze for the projects, the readings technically weren't cumulative, but you have to do them for lecture to make any sense. And lectures are engaging, so that's definitely an inventive. Prof T likes to use PollEv to make lectures more interactive. She definitely has a sense of humor which was infectious throughout the class! The only thing I didn't enjoy was probably the cold calling in lecture at the end of the semester (by our canvas numbers). I kind of felt like I was playing a twisted version of bingo twice a week, but at the same time it was kind of funny.

Strengths: encourages engagement, interesting reading material, good lectures

Weaknesses: leaves out what happened to the Chinese tradition after the early 20th century
Strength: Very interesting course, presents material in an engaging manner, manageable readings + videos
Great TFs, helped a lot with papers and to understand topics
I enjoyed reading the primary texts
I enjoyed the in-person breakout rooms! They helped me stay focused during class. Also the Kahoot was really fun.

The asynchronous and synchronous lectures were very engaging. Prof T. seemed to care a lot about her students and was very understanding. I think the assignments were sometimes unclear, and felt that sometimes we weren't equipped with the skills to do the papers/assignments. In class, we really focused on historical context, but we couldn't/shouldn't do that for the papers. I felt there was a disconnect in that regard.
The strengths of this course were the multitude of pre-lecture videos that supplemented the content.
Didnt teach the skills needed to do the projects
I think the course was well organized, but sometimes the readings would be very long and sometimes theyd be very short.

The class is actually very interesting, but I wish there was more support when it came down to the writing assignments. I also wish the last writing assignment wasn't changed from the previous two. I felt like I was finally getting a sense of how to write the kind of essay the prompt asked for and then for our last assignment the prompt got changed entirely.
I liked the breakout room discussions with peers

Strengths: Very engaging and not too time-consuming. The homework load is quite low as well
Weaknesses: A few of people take this as a mindless gut, so they don't care about the class and aren't actively engaged in the coursework

I think that the course could be structured with a bit more focus because I feel like we jumped from era to era without really addressing much of the in-between, making the class feel more like a 'greatest hits' compilation than a true overview.

This was my favorite class I've taken at Yale. It does a very good job at following the Chinese intellectual tradition from the beginning of Chinese history all the way until the May 4th movement. Very good intro to big idea. Prof T is passionate and knowledgeable and will surely make you interested in the subject.

strength: rich text, primary sources, great professor
weakness: covered topics broadly so could not dive deeper into certain things
the anonymous name calling in class was extremely nerve wracking

Strengths: Great flexibility with project assignments (if in humanities section), no exams and little homework assignments, passionate prof and TAs
Weaknesses: hard to follow at times especially as someone who is used to psets and streamlined learning

Prof T is an engaging lecturer, and the TFs were all excellent. The workload was relatively light and the texts we read were interesting. I liked the in person format of breakout rooms and enjoyed the asynchronous lectures.

I think Prof. T does a great job with lectures and encouraging participation through her "breakout rooms", which basically means discussing a prompt every class with the students around you. The readings were also not too long, which made it more enjoyable to do the homework. Overall, the workload is pretty light, but this class can still be intellectually rewarding with the right topics. I love that Prof. T removed examinations from this course as well, making it easier for us to focus on the texts. In terms of weaknesses, I think the writing section could have generally been a bit more organized at times, but I still really enjoyed my TA.

The course is well-organized and insanely interesting! Prof T is amazing and is very passionate about the subject, which made me super enthusiastic about the content. The TAs were also great, the discussion sections were always fun and engaging and I never felt lost when writing assignments. No weaknesses, fantastic course.

Strengths: Prof Lu is amazing, extremely knowledgeable, and make the extremely vast topic approachable and interesting ;; Weaknesses: I wouldn't say that there were any of this course, but I would recommend against taking it if you're not prepared to participate in class. Prof Lu tries really hard to make the coursework extremely manageable and light, but a lot of people clearly did not do the readings, and it showed in overall lack of class general discussion, which was sad since I would've loved to hear more people's thoughts.

Strengths: I think the course is very well organized. You will always know what readings were assigned and when the assignments were due. Professor Lu is really passionate about her teaching and always open to talking. 
Weaknesses: This class can have a lot of readings at times and if you get busy and fall behind, it can get really hard to catch up.

Strengths: the professor - super chill and funny, the material - very interesting

Weaknesses: teaching skills pertaining to the writing assignments specifically (maybe in section) so students know how to approach them.
The strengths of the course are the material and history we learned. It could be improved by less in-class 'group discussion time and more listening to Prof. T.

I was overall very pleased with the course, the strength I believe in our ability to express whatever we thought about the text. One way the course could be improved is perhaps in particular with the writing section, as I felt it could have been more useful to have writing workshops rather than just more discussion about the text.

strengths- very cool subject
weaknesses- sometimes didn't feel as though there was a lot of direction or structure as to how to do projects

I felt like the course content was incredibly interesting. The readings chosen to go along with the course were also incredibly compelling and well-curated. The main weakness would be that the course should have emphasized the connections between different time periods and eras earlier on, rather than talking about those connections later on--right before the projects were due.

I loved the lectures by Prof T, she loves this subject and the passion she has really shows during class. I also liked the emphasis being more on close-reading and analysis rather than on memorizing dates and events, though they are important to see progression and changes over time. Liu Laoshi who taught the Chinese section is truly incredible: she is so kind, understanding, and willing to help with anything at all. She does an amazing job making sure everyone in the section is engaged and has a chance to talk about their views and analysis. She is also very knowledgeable about the topics and expresses them with such high degree of clarity and accuracy in Chinese which I find fascinating since oftentimes I struggle with finding the right words or phrases to properly convey what I want to say.
Good breakout rooms, section activities, lectures

I enjoyed the recorded lectures online that we could watch before class, and also lectures of the class were recorded, which was helpful. We had super fun field trips to the art museum and Beinecke. The biggest con was a lack of clear feedback about the projects.

Tina Lu is a wonderful, knowledgeable, and compassionate instructor who truly does all she can to ensure the class is as fun and educational as possible. I always looked forward to this class and my section for it. It's taught very well and in a way in which it's not required you memorize every little thing in this class - rather, you take from it the key insights and skills that Prof. Lu wants you to know (like, reading a text to understand why and how someone conveys their thoughts in that way). Readings were relevant, a decent amount, but you didn't have to read them to follow along in class. Weaknesses: location (Bass Center is a trek), large class size, not getting the slides after class.
It was low stress, but I think the prompts for projects were very vague.

Strength: really great lecturing, interesting and diverse pick of course materials, and well organized. 
Weaknesses: the assignments instructions should have been more clear in what Prof T. wants from her students. It's very vague and academic, and not particularly easily accessible for first-years.

Professor was very enthusiastic about the material, and the material was very interesting. Discussion was promoted and the course was very engaging. Prof T always made sure the lectures were always fun and tried to frame everything as we might understand them in a 21st century lens, which definitely helped engagement

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes. It's an interesting course that allows you to learn the basics of Chinese history and philosophy without becoming too intensive.
Yes! A very good survey course that anyone should take. Prof Lu cares a lot about her students; go to her office hours!

Yes, but don't go in thinking it's a gut. There are lots of readings and the only way to get anything out of this course is to be very engaged in the material. If you have interest in Chinese literature and philosophy then I would recommend.
Yes absolutely! Especially for students of Chinese descent. I found myself looking forward to lecture every week.

Yes  this course is a relatively low workload class that gives a great introduction to the history of Chinese literature and philosophy. The diversity of primary sources covered (ancient poems, treatises for emperors, public pamphlets, etc.) is impressive.
Yes! I love Prof. T and I looked forward to this class every week. If you are looking for a chill 5th credit this would be the one! And you really get a lot out of it too.

It is a good way to get broad knowledge about China especially its culture in the past but is relatively surface level and should be avoided if you want a deeper more analytical course that focuses more on specifics
Yes! Especially for people interested in exploring Chinese history/culture this is a really great course to take.
I would recommend if you are looking for a 5th class or lower workload class. I really appreciated how there were only 3 big assignments of short length.
I would recommend this course to another student who is interested in Chinese history or culture.
Yes, I would if anyone would want to branch themselves out and try something new.

It depends. The lecture content was very interesting. At the start of the semester, readings are also pretty short and manageable, although they do increase as the semester goes on. However, lecture attendance is required, and attendance is taken, so be prepared for that if you are planning on taking this class. The professor also implemented a cold calling system partway through the semester which added a lot of unnecessary stress to the class. If you take the writing section, be prepared to struggle a lot with the writing assignments. The prompts for the writing assignments are very difficult since you are required to write so much about such short passages (one of the assignments was a 5-7 page paper based on a close reading of about 20-40 words). Grading can also feel a bit arbitrary.
Yes, this is a great class if youre interested in getting an intro to Chinese history & ancient texts
Yes. It is a great introduction to premodern Chinese thought and not too intensive of a writing credit.
YES!!! I could not recommend a course more strongly. This is my favorite class I've taken at Yale and it will introduce you to an entirely new cannon.

Yes, this is a great overview course of the Chinese Tradition. It is not a super demanding class so this is great for someone who's looking to learn more about this topic if they have a heavy course load. It is one of those 'you get out what you put into it' classes so definitely create incentives for yourself to be engaged or you can easily get nothing out of this course.
Yes!!! Prof. T is lovely, but it's not a gut by any means, especially for the writing sections
Yes
Yes! If you're looking to have a broader view of Chinese history through texts and classical documents, it's a great first course to get an overview!

Yes, I think this class has a lot to offer in terms of enriching your knowledge on pre-modern China. Prof T and the TFs put in a lot of effort to make the class engaging and interesting, and there is a large focus on learning and analyzing rather than memorizing random facts. The workload is very manageable and the content is interesting.

Yeah! I would recommend this course to people who want a course that can be interesting with a light workload. Especially if you're Chinese-American, I think this course can really be engaging at certain points and teach you a lot about Chinese culture that you wouldn't get otherwise.

Yes. Do it. One of the best classes I took at Yale. The selection of texts was great, the lectures were fascinating and the assignments were relatively low-stress but very engaging. I also genuinely feel that this course made me a better reader and changed the way I think about historical texts. It's quite gutty if you are a good writer or have a background in the humanities, but Prof T is a fantastic lecturer and it you get a lot out of the course if you put in the work. Can't recommend enough, as a Wr or Hu credit or when you just need a good class - it was a breath of fresh air during an otherwise stressful semester fulfilling other various requirements for my major.
Yes, absolutely! Took this along with my Chinese language class and it was a wonderful supplement to the course, by delving into history, philosophy, and culture.

Yes! If you're looking for an introduction to EAST/EALL or just want to know more about the Chinese academic canon (ie. Confucianism, Daoism, Buddhism, etc.), this is a great class to introduce yourself to various Chinese thinkers within those fields.
Yes, for sure. If youre for a fifth credit, or a HU credit, Id highly recommend. It really dismantles any prejudices you might have against China and at least understand where they stem from.
The class was pretty good; the assignments were three papers + mini-responses, so workload-wise not too bad. This is a class where you get out what you put in.
Yep of course! Be sure that you are genuinely interested in the Chinese Tradition!
yes, if you are very interested in Chinese philosophy. if you are looking for a history class about more recent events, this is not the class for you. we covered philosopher, dynasties, etc.

I would for sure recommend the course to other students--no matter their major. The course content is incredibly compelling, and if you are looking for a writing or humanities credit, this class is a great place to get one.

Yes! absolutely!!! It is an amazing course to take even if you are not a humanities major and I highly recommend that anyone who has even an inkling of curiosity about Chinese culture and tradition take it. Prof T is a great lecturer and the section professors are also very knowledgeable and there to support you. The workload isn't too bad, just a pre-lecture video that introduces the concepts and some readings that you prepare and think about for class. APart from that, there are some very chill short and quick activities every 2 weeks or so, but the main portion of your grade comes from the 3 projects done over the semester.
Yes if interested about Chinese culture. The class is fast paced and covers a lot.

Absolutely! I am not an EALL major, nor will I take any more EALL classes, but I truly believe I learned so so much from this class, even if I don't remember all of the facts along the way. I think this was a great class to get a good sense of what the humanities are like. It's so interdisciplinary, and you can take a lot out of it, especially if you aren't as familiar with Chinese history, culture, and philosophy. It's a very chill class (Hu, not Wr) and honestly just super cool.
It was a good extra class. you gain how much you put into the class. The content is engaging, but its hard to stay engaged throughout the semester.

Yes! I was able to engage with the texts in a closer view than I had ever before  this course focused so much on getting deeply into the writing and analysis, in a way that challenged me because I have always written with a more overarching focus. I really did enjoy learning about the different artistic mediums, such as Tang Poetry or calligraphy that was part of the intellectual tradition, rather than just philosophical texts.
Yes - fun course, interesting course material, enthusiastic professor
